.\" Comprehensive manpage for zpwr — meta page covering everything.
.\" Contact: https://github.com/MenkeTechnologies/zpwr
.TH ZPWRALL 1 "2026-07-13" "zpwr v48.9.4" "ZPWR Manual"
.SH NAME
zpwrall \- comprehensive ZPWR reference: dispatcher, every verb, every environment variable, file layout, tmux, keybindings, caches
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B zpwr
.RI [ VERB " [" ARGS ...]]
.br
.B zpwr
.BR \-h " | " \-? " | " \-\-help
.br
.B zpwr
.BR \-V " | " \-\-version
.SH OVERVIEW
This is the meta-manual for ZPWR \(em the equivalent of
.BR zshall (1)
for the
.B zpwr
environment. It contains every section of
.BR zpwr (1)
plus full enumerations of:
.IP \(bu 2
all 461 dispatcher verbs (alphabetic, with short description and the
underlying command/function);
.IP \(bu 2
all 88+ documented
.B ZPWR_*
environment variables;
.IP \(bu 2
the canonical install layout and per-directory purpose;
.IP \(bu 2
tmux prefix, key bindings, and synced-pane semantics;
.IP \(bu 2
zsh keymap layout (viins / vicmd / menuselect / visual / listscroll / viopp);
.IP \(bu 2
caching and compilation surfaces
.RB ( .zwc ,
ctags, gtags, env cache);
.IP \(bu 2
log levels and log destinations;
.IP \(bu 2
plugin/zinit interaction.
.PP
The page is intentionally exhaustive. For a curated cross-section, see
.BR zpwr (1)
or run
.BR "zpwr help" .
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B zpwr
is the master dispatcher for the ZPWR terminal environment \(em a
high-voltage zsh-on-zinit cockpit weaponized with custom zsh, bash, vimL,
and
.I stryke
code. The
.B zpwr
shell function is defined at
.I $ZPWR/autoload/common/zpwr
and sources
.I $ZPWR_VERBS_FILE
.RI ( $ZPWR/env/zpwr.zsh )
on every invocation. That file declares the
.B ZPWR_VERBS
associative array, looks up
.IR VERB ,
splits its value on the literal
.B =
into
.IR command = description ,
and dispatches the command \(em forwarding any remaining
.I ARGS
quoted via
.BR ${(q)@} .
.PP
With no arguments,
.B zpwr
.BR cd s
to
.BR $ZPWR ,
the install root (typically
.IR ~/.zpwr ).
.PP
ZPWR ships:
.IP \(bu 2
461+ dispatcher verbs across 26 alphabetic groups;
.IP \(bu 2
538+ autoloaded zsh functions in
.IR $ZPWR/autoload/ ;
.IP \(bu 2
174+ standalone scripts in
.IR $ZPWR/scripts/ ;
.IP \(bu 2
147+ test cases under
.IR $ZPWR/tests/ ;
.IP \(bu 2
a full tmux cockpit
.RI ( $ZPWR/tmux/ );
.IP \(bu 2
the ZPWR Encyclopedia (LaTeX + HTML +
.B zpwr docs
wizard pages) under
.IR $ZPWR/docs/ .
.SH DISPATCH MODEL
For each call
.RB \(lq "zpwr VERB ARGS..." \(rq:
.IP 1. 4
If
.B VERB
is empty,
.BR cd
to
.BR $ZPWR .
.IP 2. 4
If
.B VERB
matches
.BR \-V " | " \-\-version ,
print the banner via
.B zpwrAbout
piped to a pager.
.IP 3. 4
If
.B VERB
matches
.BR \-h " | " \-? " | " \-\-help ,
list every verb in color via
.B zpwrListVerbsColor
piped to a pager.
.IP 4. 4
End-of-options
.B \-\-
markers are consumed; the next arg becomes
.IR VERB .
.IP 5. 4
.B VERB
is looked up in
.BR ZPWR_VERBS .
The value has the form
.IR cmd = description ;
.B cmd
may be a single command or a
.B ;
-separated chain. Each component is dispatched: aliases via
.BR eval ,
otherwise via
.B "eval cmd ${(q)@}"
to preserve quoting.
.IP 6. 4
Unknown verbs print
.RB \(lq "Unknown subcommand: \(aqVERB\(aq" \(rq
to stderr and return 1.
.PP
Multiple verbs can resolve to the same command (aliases). For example
.BR doctor ", " doc ", " checkup
all dispatch to
.BR zpwrDoctor .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-? ", " \-\-help
List every verb with colorized descriptions in a pager.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Show the ZPWR banner / version in a pager.
.TP
.B \-\-
End-of-options marker; next arg is
.IR VERB .
.SH VERBS
The complete verb table follows, alphabetized. Each entry shows the verb
name, a short description, and the underlying
.IR command
or
.I function
that backs it. Aliases (multiple verbs sharing one description+command)
are visible by repetition.
